[normal]Designation and putti[bold]ng campaign arguments to voters[bold]1.21
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]he issue of 
[normal]whether the referendum is likely to stimulate a level of debate which would generate willing and a
[normal]ble applicants for designation
[normal] 
[normal]as lead campaigner
[normal]s
[normal] on both sides 
[normal]of the argument 
[normal]is one that needs early consideration. 
[normal]1.22
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The generic 
[normal]statutory designation process 
[normal]in PPERA 
[normal]relies on the assumption that there will be campaign groups on either side of the re
[normal]ferendum question which are willing and able to use the benefits of designation to mount a lead campaign. If that is not the case – either because most prospective campaigners are on one side of the debate, or because a campaigner sees tactical advantage i
[normal]n not seeking designation – then the referendum campaign, and the process of putting the campaign arguments to voters, 
[normal]is likely to
[normal] suffer.
[normal]1.23
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A
[normal]t the 2011 referendum in
[normal] Wales, we were unable to designate lead campaigners because there was no willing and able 
[normal]applicant for the 
[normal]‘no’ outcome.  
[normal]1.24
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We recommended[bold] in 2011 that when considering the case for future referendums, legislators should take into account whether the referendum is likely to stimulate a level of debate which would generate willing and able appli
[normal]cants for designation. We would of 
[normal]course be happy to work with the Government to consider how to take th
[normal]is recommendation into account.
[normal]1.25
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We also recommended
[normal] in 2011 
[normal]that t
[normal]he Government should take steps to reduce the potential advantages to a prospective l
[normal]ead campaigner of deciding not to apply for designation. In 2012, the Government responded to this recommendation by saying
[normal]:
[normal]‘
[normal]Designated organisations are important to the referendum process as they are a source of public awareness about the issues at hand
[normal]. It is important that support be provided for them through the legislative framework. Clearly, it runs counter to the interests of voters if there is any incentive for campaigners to refrain from applying to become designated organisations, as this may im
[normal]pede the proper development of public understanding during a referendum campaign…… The Government is therefore considering carefully how the designation process might be improved
[normal]’
[normal]1.26
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Scottish Government has addressed this recommendation 
[normal]in the 
[normal]Scottish 
[normal]Independence Referendum Act 2013 by providing for the Commission to designate for only one outcome if there are not willing and abl
[normal]e applicants for both outcomes.
