[normal]National Assembly [bold]for Wales electoral arrangements[bold]F[bold]ive [bold]year fixed terms[bold]1.34
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]he draft Bill
[normal] would lengthen
[normal] Assembly terms from four to five years. 
[normal]Whilst the C
[normal]ommission does not have a 
[normal]specific 
[normal]view on the question of whether an Assembly term should be a four or five year fixed term, we 
[normal]do
[normal] 
[normal]give
[normal] 
[normal]our 
[normal]views on particular combinations of elections.
[normal] 
[normal]The Commission’
[normal]s position is that each individual proposal should b
[normal]e considered on its merits and w
[normal]e advise on the particular risks and how they could be managed.
[normal] 
[normal]Our priority is that a poll
[normal] is well-run and delivered in a way that is easy for voters to 
[normal]understand and par
[normal]ticipate in.
[normal]1.35
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The election schedule is
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.36
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The combination of a UK Parliamentary general election, Welsh general election and Police and Crime Commissioner elections in 2020 would present significan
[normal]t challenges for voters. I
[normal]t would mea
[normal]n each voter
[normal] 
[normal]casting ballots
[normal] in up to three differently-drawn constituencies
[normal] and
[normal] 
[normal]an electoral region;
[normal] on four separate ballot papers and using
[normal] 
[normal]three different electoral systems
[normal].
[normal] It would also prove challenging for political parties and candidates, not least because of the risk of one campaign overshadowing another and the communication issues that campaigning across multiple elections presents. 
[normal]There would also be 
[normal]a
[normal]dministrative 
[normal]challenges
[normal] for
[normal] Ret
[normal]urning Off
[normal]icers
[normal]. Overall, these
[normal] issues would bring significant risks to ensuring well-run elections.
[normal] 
[normal]1.37
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Moving 
[normal]the Assembly term to five years avoids 
[normal]the risks inherent in 
[normal]combining three sets of elections i
[normal]n 2020
[normal], although 
[normal]it 
[normal]does then bri
[normal]ng
[normal] 
[normal]combination with local government elections
[normal] in Wales
[normal] 
[normal]in 2021
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]In th
[normal]at combination, each voter would cast ballots
[normal] in 
[normal]a constituency
[normal], 
[normal]an electoral region
[normal] and 
[normal]a local ward
[normal], on three ballot papers and using two electoral systems. There would be 
[normal]risks
[normal] to add
[normal]ress
[normal], but less so
[normal] than 
[normal]in 
[normal]2020.
[normal]Restore the right for candidates to stand on both a constituency and regional list during the Assembly elections[bold]1.38
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]he draft 
[normal]Bill
[normal] provides for
[normal] the removal of the restriction on standing for election for both cons
[normal]tituency
[normal] and 
[normal]electoral regions.
[normal] It
[normal] should be straightforward for people to participate 
[normal]in elections, whether voting or campaigning. This means there should be no unnecessary barriers to standing for election. We made our view clear when the initial proposals to prohibit dual candidacy in W
[normal]ales were published as part of the Government of Wales Bill 2006 that we did not believe that the case for introducing the change had been made, on the evidence available at the time. 
[normal]1.39
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To our knowledge, no further evidence has become available that would s
[normal]uggest that the prohibition should be retained. It continues to be the case that there is no similar prohibition for candidates in Scottish Parliament elections, where the same electoral system is in use
[normal].
[normal]  We agree, therefore, that candidates should be abl
[normal]e to stand in a constituency and a region in the same Assembly election. 
[normal]Ensure that Assembly Members cannot be MPs at the same time[bold]1.40
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]he draft 
[normal]Bill
[normal] provides for
[normal] the disqualification of MPs from membership of the Assembly. 
[normal]While we do
[normal] not have a specific 
[normal]view on the question
[normal] of multiple mandates, issues to be considered are what the electorate
[normal] expect
[normal]s of their representatives and how 
[normal]representative
[normal]s
[normal] ensure the best possible leve
[normal]l
[normal] of service
[normal].
[normal] Can this be
[normal] achieved by representing the electorate
[normal] at a variety 
[normal]of different levels (for example at the UK Parliament and the National Assembly for Wales) and the experience which this brings about or should the focus be
[normal] entirely on one legislature?
